{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":4571,"record_hash":"sha256:fc8d6ff8ae701ffa19168889909b7b5c268eda6c8ffbeb3544d3ee3443e161ed","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:51:42.959Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:38-46) [added]\n[P2] Sensitive keys do not force redaction\n\nThe object walk redacts string values only by value shape, without considering the field name. Low-entropy values under keys like `token`, `api_key`, `secret`, `password`, or `authorization` can survive and still be reported as unredacted. A tiny key denylist for string values feels POC-sized and high value.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:99-112) [added]\n[P2] Prefixed UUIDs can still be redacted\n\nUUIDs are preserved only when the whole candidate is exactly a UUID. Since `_`, `/`, and `=` are candidate bytes, common strings like `[REDACTED:entropy]` or `[REDACTED:entropy]` can be scanned as one high-entropy candidate and redacted even though UUIDs are intended to survive.\n\n## Finding 3 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:40-46) [added]\n[P3] JSON keys bypass redaction\n\nObject keys are copied unchanged, so a transcript record that puts a token-like string in a JSON member name will store it verbatim. That is probably less common than value leakage, but if the redactor claims to protect stored `source_record`, this should either be explicitly scoped as value-only or handled with collision-safe key placeholders.\n\n## Finding 4 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:115-119) [added]\n[P3] Git SHAs are now likely redacted\n\nThe long-hex rule catches 32+ character high-entropy hex strings, which includes normal Git object IDs in transcript/tool output. This is a defensible privacy tradeoff for the POC, but it will erase useful provenance unless we add contextual exemptions later.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nLets fix:\n\nPrefixed UUIDs can still be redacted\nand \n\nGit SHAs are now likely redacted\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:51:42.959Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user","content":[{"type":"input_text","text":"\n# Review findings:\n\n## Finding 1 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:38-46) [added]\n[P2] Sensitive keys do not force redaction\n\nThe object walk redacts string values only by value shape, without considering the field name. Low-entropy values under keys like `token`, `api_key`, `secret`, `password`, or `authorization` can survive and still be reported as unredacted. A tiny key denylist for string values feels POC-sized and high value.\n\n## Finding 2 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:99-112) [added]\n[P2] Prefixed UUIDs can still be redacted\n\nUUIDs are preserved only when the whole candidate is exactly a UUID. Since `_`, `/`, and `=` are candidate bytes, common strings like `[REDACTED:entropy]` or `[REDACTED:entropy]` can be scanned as one high-entropy candidate and redacted even though UUIDs are intended to survive.\n\n## Finding 3 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:40-46) [added]\n[P3] JSON keys bypass redaction\n\nObject keys are copied unchanged, so a transcript record that puts a token-like string in a JSON member name will store it verbatim. That is probably less common than value leakage, but if the redactor claims to protect stored `source_record`, this should either be explicitly scoped as value-only or handled with collision-safe key placeholders.\n\n## Finding 4 (crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs:115-119) [added]\n[P3] Git SHAs are now likely redacted\n\nThe long-hex rule catches 32+ character high-entropy hex strings, which includes normal Git object IDs in transcript/tool output. This is a defensible privacy tradeoff for the POC, but it will erase useful provenance unless we add contextual exemptions later.\n\n## My request for Codex:\nLets fix:\n\nPrefixed UUIDs can still be redacted\nand \n\nGit SHAs are now likely redacted\n"}]}}}